"Perspektiven für die sino-amerikanischen Beziehungen 2019" translates to "Prospects for Sino-American Relations in 2019" in English.
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations had a destabilizing effect on wide parts of Asia.
One year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly extravagant "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
One year later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the United States with China with "strategic competition."
Added to this is the fact that the US, European, and Chinese domestic economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty in financial markets, with growth slowing down in China and Europe, and higher interest rates beginning to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of the atomic negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
So, what were the prospects for relations between the USA and China in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and China's import decisions regarding this will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible in the meantime, although the complexity of the topic could extend the intended timeframe.
If each customs issue were negotiated separately, a year could easily pass.
If Chinese economic reformers were to adopt a more drastic approach instead, by committing over time to the abolition of all tariffs and urging the Americans to do the same, faster results might be achieved.
This would, however, go against Chinese trade officials who have been trained for decades to be sparing with their praise, let alone giving it all at once.
The reform of so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Despite this, a reform would be something different from how contractual agreements could be interpreted in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property, however, is extremely problematic.
Earlier agreements made under President Barack Obama's administration could be reaffirmed again.
The enforcement of their rights or legal action against infringements of intellectual property remains, however, a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism involves subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to trade arbitration courts based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing intellectual property protection.
If China raises objections, it could develop its own international trade dispute settlement procedure that is based in China.
For that, it would however need to include qualified foreigners in its arbitration panel to strengthen its international credibility.
No one has trust in Chinese trade courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil courts within its judicial system, even though the criminal court remains subject to political control.
The American concerns regarding the state subsidies within the framework of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be easily resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide some level of state support to their indigenous technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a specific company, it would be difficult to enforce.
I am not optimistic about reaching an agreement in this area.
Maybe America just needs to defeat China by increasing public investments in research and development in the areas of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out that China offers customs reforms to the rest of the international community.
This could lead China over time to decide on such a drastic step not only with the USA but also with all member states of the World Trade Organization to agree on free trade.
In this way, it would offer China an almost irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to curb the trend toward protectionism.
In the event of such a shift, China could invite the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join it, thereby circumventing the US (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of the first actions of Trump's administration) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and market liberalization.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China joining the TPP have diminished since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's most recent visit to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in relation to the USA, China is likely to aim in its general foreign and security policy in 2019 at reducing conflicts in its relationships with other countries.
The relationships with Japan have already begun to normalize.
The latest data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a clear reduction in Chinese incursions into the waters around the Senkaku/Diaoyu islands in the East China Sea.
China also wants to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) over the South China Sea through the accelerated negotiation of a "Code of Conduct."
Moreover, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could start moderating its stance toward Taiwan in light of the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, who advocates independence, in local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the USA continues with further significant weapons sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
There continue to be incidents at sea in the South China Sea involving the USA, and the conflict could escalate if the USA more aggressively underscores their stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
China will continue to implement its major project "New Silk Road" across all of Eurasia.
In the last few months, however, the initiative in China has caused less political controversy.
There are already discussions among Chinese officials about revising certain aspects of the Belt and Road Initiative, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financial sustainability of the New Silk Road.
Thus, triumphant reports about the New Silk Road could be less frequent in 2019.
Furthermore, China is likely to strengthen and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It is likely to continue appearing as a new advocate for the WHO and to retain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More sober-minded representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially given that the USA consistently shows disdain for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the United States and reduce tensions in its relationships with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a more solid judgment about the future of U.S. policy: the implications of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would in any way alter the new U.S. strategy.
Despite having concluded that America's stance toward China has undergone profound changes, they remain uncertain about the specific form these changes take and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is called for.
